<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="triangularia species group">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona triangularia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona triangularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
Based on 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.1968.tb00369.x" author="Wilkinson, C" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Zoological Society of London" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="407 - 517" refId="B26" refString="Wilkinson, C, 1968. A Taxonomic revision of the genus Ditrigona (Lepidoptera: Drepanidae: Drepaninae). Transactions of the Zoological Society of London 31 (4): 407 - 517, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.1968.tb00369.x" title="A Taxonomic revision of the genus Ditrigona (Lepidoptera: Drepanidae: Drepaninae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.1968.tb00369.x" volume="31" year="1968">Wilkinson (1968)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Jiang, S" journalOrPublisher="Entomotaxonomia" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="81 - 88" refId="B12" refString="Jiang, S, Han, HX, 2019. A new species of Ditrigona Moore (Lepidoptera: Drepanidae) in China, with a checklist to the triangularia -group. Entomotaxonomia 41 (2): 81 - 88" title="A new species of Ditrigona Moore (Lepidoptera: Drepanidae) in China, with a checklist to the triangularia - group." volume="41" year="2019">Jiang and Han (2019)</bibRefCitation>
, the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona triangularia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona triangularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group contains ten species, in which 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona triangularia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona triangularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Moore), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1922" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona regularis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="regularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona regularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Warren, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chu &amp; Wang" authorityYear="1988" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona uniuncusa" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uniuncusa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona uniuncusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chu &amp; Wang, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jiang &amp; Han" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona tenuiata" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuiata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona tenuiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Jiang &amp; Han bear elongate posterior projections of the hind wings (tail process); the other six species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilkinson" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona titana" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="titana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona titana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wilkinson, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Oberthuer" baseAuthorityYear="1923" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona pomenaria" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomenaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona pomenaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Oberthür">Oberthuer</normalizedToken>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilkinson" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona typhodes" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="typhodes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona typhodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wilkinson, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Oberthuer" baseAuthorityYear="1923" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona polyobotaria" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polyobotaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona polyobotaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Oberthür">Oberthuer</normalizedToken>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilkinson" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona sciara" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sciara">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona sciara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wilkinson, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1893" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona fasciata" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Hampson) lack the tail process. The first nine species are recorded in China, and three new species (
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. sinespina" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="sinespina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. sinespina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. parva" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. concava" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="concava">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. concava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with the tail process are described in this work.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
The species with a tail process on the hind wing have quite distinct wing patterns: the hind wing has the postmedial and submarginal lines approaching each other near the anal angle, and bears a small black patch at the upper angle of the tail. The species lacking a tail process resemble some species of the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">mytylata</emphasis>
species group, in that they have transverse lines which often resemble a narrow band. In the male genitalia, the valva is characterized by having a small flap-like extension. The species with a tail process can also be distinguished by the large rounded socii and the stout aedeagus bearing a brush-like cornutus. In the species lacking a tail process, the aedeagus is narrow, straight or bent, and the cornutus is a simple process or absent. The eighth sternite is small, shallowly concave or protruding in species with a tail process, and the eighth tergite almost unmodified. Both eighth tergite and sternite often possess octavals in the species lacking a tail process. In the female genitalia, the ostium bursae is usually large, and the ductus bursae is often indiscernible, but wide and obvious in 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. typhodes" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="typhodes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. typhodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The corpus bursae bears a small accessory sac in species with a tail process. (modified from Wilkinson, 1968)
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
16 DAN barcoding sequences were obtained for 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. regularis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="regularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. regularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. triangularia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="triangularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. triangularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. tenuiata" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="tenuiata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. tenuiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. concava" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="concava">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. concava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. parva" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., and 
<taxonomicName family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. sinespina" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="sinespina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. sinespina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., and the six species are clearly separated from each other in the COI barcode fragment (fig. 178). The genetic distance between these species is 8.92% (min. 7.16%, max. 12.32%).
</paragraph>
